ticipating in the Japanese colonial legal system. In turn, the Japanese doctrine of promoting progressive legal rights would prove advantageous to them. Following female plaintiffs and their civil disputes from the precolonial Choson dynasty through colonial times and into postcolonial reforms, this book presents a new and groundbreaking story about Korean women's legal struggles, revealing their surprising collaborative relationship with the colonial state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aDomestic relationszKoreay20th century. 0aDomestic relations. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etczKoreay20th century. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zKoreay20th century. 0aWomen. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  acivil courts.  acivilization.  acolonial times.  ajapan.  ajapanese colonial legal system.  ajapanese colonial rule of korea.  ajapanese family laws.  ajapanese motto.  akorean women.  akorean womens legal struggles.  ameiji civil code.  apassive victims.  apatriarchal biases.  apost colonial reforms.  apre colonial chosen dynasty.  apromoting progress.  athrough the lens of women.  avictimized women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520972506zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520972506zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520972506.jpg  a978-3-11-066767-7 UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA